narratives.question_text: What knowledge, skills, and insights did you develop by taking this course?
comments: We focused on practicing reading and writing
A better knowledge of Chinese literature and recent Chinese history through Su Laoshi. Not much improvement in my spoken Chinese, though.

I learned many Chinese speaking skills through class reading and final presentation. I also learned many unique Chinese phrases, including both their meaning and their origin. I also learned a lot about recent Chinese history.
Learnt a lot about Chinese culture and history. The course readings were absolutely great.
Reading in Chinese fiction. Literally analysis and strong verbal communication skills. Also extensive knowledge of Chinese contemporary history.

narratives.question_text: What are the strengths and weaknesses of this course and how could it be improved?
comments:
Strengths: great selection of readings
Weaknesses: we didn't have a lot of time for discussion in class about the texts

This courses strength is Su Laoshi and his basically endless knowledge of Chinese literature. To give an example of what that means, he personally knows most of the authors that you read in the course. 

Its main weakness is that you dont get much of an opportunity to practice your spoken Chinese unless you go to non-mandatory Chinese tables. Su laoshi mostly just talks to you, which is often useful, but theres hardly ever any real class discussion.
It was an extremely interactive course, I learned a lot through Professor Su's story-telling teaching style.

strength: very fun and eye-opening 
weakness: na

narratives.question_text: Would you recommend this course to another student? Please explain.
comments: Yes, if just to take a class with Su Laoshi while youre at Yale.

I would recommend this course to anyone who wishes to develop a strong understanding of the Chinese language, improve speaking and writing skills, and understand contemporary Chinese authors and history.
